Imposter syndrome âœ¨ I have never talked about it but experienced it so so many times and I am sure you have too ğŸ¥² 

So what is it? ğŸ¤¨
It is the feeling of self-doubt and personal incompetence that persist despite your education, experience, and accomplishments ğŸ˜”
â€œWhat am I doing here?â€ â€œI do not belong hereâ€ â€œEveryone must be so much better than meâ€ â€œI am not worthy of the jobâ€

I never knew something like this existed and found out after I quit my first engineering job.
So why am I talking about this?
Because you might feel the same and it is completely normal ğŸ™‚

Imposter feelings represent a conflict between your own self-perception and the way others perceive you. To counter these feelings, you might end up working harder and holding yourself to ever higher standards. This pressure can eventually take a toll on your emotional well-being and your performance.

My advice on overcoming it: If your colleagues and your team/company is happy with your results and work, just calm down a little. Believe in yourself and your abilities! Stop comparing yourself to others. You will eventually feel better over time as you get used to your colleagues and the environment you work in.

A structure is a user-defined data type in C/C++. A structure creates a data type that can be used to group items of possibly different types into a single type. 

In C++, a structure is the same as a class except for a few differences. The most important of them is security. A Structure is not secure and cannot hide its implementation details from the end user while a class is secure and can hide its programming and designing details.
